---

## 9. Documentation Rules

Update documentation when changing:
- architecture
- voice provider behavior
- environment variables
- Docker services
- API endpoints
- setup steps
- security model

README.md should stay practical and setup-focused.

ARCHITECTURE.md should explain how the system works.

VOICE_PROVIDERS.md should explain provider tradeoffs and integration details.

ROADMAP.md should track milestones without pretending future work is already implemented.

---

## 10. Code Quality Rules

Frontend:
- Use TypeScript.
- Prefer typed props and explicit state names.
- Keep components small.
- Avoid giant all-in-one pages.
- Keep provider logic out of presentation components.

Backend:
- Use type hints.
- Use Pydantic schemas for request/response models.
- Keep API routes thin.
- Put business logic in services.
- Keep provider-specific logic behind interfaces/classes.

Testing:
- Add tests for service logic where practical.
- At minimum, keep health checks and smoke tests working.

Formatting:
- Use consistent formatting.
- Do not introduce inconsistent styles.

---

## 11. Latency Rules

The project prioritizes natural conversation latency.

Do:
- stream whenever possible
- avoid unnecessary backend hops
- keep OpenAI Realtime as the low-latency default
- keep ElevenLabs path modular for quality/custom voice testing

Do not:
- wait for full long responses before speaking when streaming is possible
- perform heavy memory/tool work on every short utterance
- add slow blocking calls to the voice loop

---

## 12. Future Module Boundaries

Do not implement these in v0.1 unless explicitly requested:

- real long-term memory
- Home Assistant control
- desktop automation
- browser automation
- Jetson vision
- Raspberry Pi satellites
- proactive scheduling
- OpenClaw integration
- payment/purchase actions

For now, create clean placeholders only.

---

## 13. Assistant Personality Direction

The UI and prompts should support a calm, concise, useful assistant.

Default behavior:
- natural spoken responses
- short answers unless asked for detail
- no excessive enthusiasm
- one follow-up question maximum
- permission before real-world actions

Do not make the assistant roleplay excessively.
It should feel like a reliable operating assistant, not a fantasy chatbot.

---

## 14. Definition of Done

A change is done only when:
- code runs or is clearly scaffolded
- environment variables are documented
- Docker setup still makes sense
- no secrets are committed
- related docs are updated
- no unrelated files were modified
- future TODOs are clearly marked
